column12: RECURSIVE LOCKING OF A THREAD-SHARED RESOURCE
column13: A method for implementing process thread locking operations includes defining a lock structure having data fields that include a process thread identifier and a shared object identifier that uniquely identifies a shared object subject to lock operations. The method also includes using the lock structure to build a lock table. The lock table includes lock structures for each process thread in the process and is searchable in response to a request for a shared object from a calling thread. The method also includes determining a lock status of the shared object. The lock status indicates whether the shared object is currently locked by the calling process thread. In response to the lock status, the method includes obtaining a lock on the shared object when the request is for a lock, and releasing a lock on the shared object when the request is to unlock the shared object
column15: BANKS LISA D;;KEENAGHAN JASON A
column32: Christian Haack, Reasoning about Java's Reentrant Locks, 2008.

column12: Controlled atmosphere when sintering a frit to a glass plate
column13: A method is described herein for controlling the oxygen level within an oven while sintering a frit to a glass plate where the sintered frit and glass plate are subsequently sealed to another glass plate to form a sealed glass package. Examples of the sealed glass package include a light-emitting device (e.g., organic light emitting diode (OLED) device), a photovoltaic device, a food container, and a medicine container.

column12: System, method and computer program product for data mining in a three-dimensional multi-user environment
column13: A data mining system, method and computer program product is provided for tracking user behavior in a three-dimensional (3D) multi-user environment. The system includes server side components that simulate the 3D multi-user environment and objects therein, and a plurality of clients connected to the server side components via a network. The server side components maintain data mining pylons that generate data mining facts concerning the location of objects in the 3D multi-user environment, as well as objects with usage triggers that detect when an avatar interacts with an object and generate a data mining fact in response. The server side components data also generate data mining facts related to user login and registration, commerce, communication, world and object state, user relationships, surveys, advertising, and customer-submitted content. Data mining facts are stored in one or more data warehousing files and may be analyzed to discover, predict or confirm trends in user behavior and preferences. The data warehousing files may also be linked to external data mining information generated by other real-world systems and commercial entities.
column15: O' ROURKE KRISTEN P;;BANKS DOUGLAS S;;MCHUGH JASON G

column12: Laser containing a distributed gain medium
column13: A laser device which may be used as an oscillator or amplifier comprising a chamber having a volume formed therein and a gain medium within the volume. The gain medium comprises solid-state elements containing active laser ion distributed within the volume. A cooling fluid flows about the solid-state elements and a semiconductor laser diode provides optical pump radiation into the volume of the laser chamber such that laser emission from the device passes through the gain medium and the fluid. The laser device provides the advantages of a solid-state gain medium laser (e.g., diode-pumping, high power density, etc), but enables operation at higher average power and beam quality than would be achievable from a pure solid-state medium.
column15: PERRY MICHAEL D;;BANKS PAUL S;;ZWEIBACK JASON;;SCHLEICHER ROBERT W

column12: Method of making elemental materials and alloys
column13: A method of producing an elemental material or an alloy thereof from a halide or mixtures of halides is provided. The halide or mixtures thereof are contacted with a reducing gas in the presence of reductant material, preferably in sufficient quantity to convert the halide to the elemental material or alloy and to maintain the temperature of the reactants at a temperature lower than the boiling point of the reductant material at atmospheric pressure or the sintering temperature of the produced elemental material or alloy.

The gain medium (14) comprises a solid-state element containing active laser ion distributed within the volume. A cooling fluid (16) flows about the solid-state element and a semiconductor laser diode (18) provides optical pump radiation into the volume of the laser chamber (12) such that laser emission from the device passes through the gain medium (14) and the fluid (16). The laser device (10) provides the advantages of a solid-state gain medium laser (e,g. diode-pumping, high power density, etc.), but enables operation at higher average power and beam quality than would be achievable from a pure solid-state medium.

column12: LASER CONTAINING DISTRIBUTED GAIN MEDIUM
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a laser device whose average power output is not restricted by thermal stress, to meet a thermal limit of solid laser, and to achieve high average power.

SOLUTION: A laser device (10) mounted with a chamber (22) having an inner region and a gain medium, and usable as an oscillator or an amplifier includes solid elements (14) containing active laser ions distributed within the volume. Cooling fluid (16) flows around the solid elements and a semiconductor laser diode (18) provides optical pump radiation into the volume of the laser chamber (12) such that laser emission from the device passes through the gain medium (14) and the fluid (16). The laser device (10) provides advantages of solid-state gain medium laser (such as diode-pumping, high power density), but enables operation at higher average power and beam quality than would be achievable from a pure solid-state medium.

column12: Environmental condition control based on sensed conditions and related methods
column13: An apparatus is provided for controlling environmental conditions using a fan and a light in connection with a building having a space including a partition, such as a wall. The apparatus may include a control adapted for being mounted to the partition and for coordinating the control of the fan and the light based on a sensed condition, such as temperature or occupancy. Groups of like devices for controlling environmental conditions may be similarly controlled, such as using control. Control may also provide an indication of an operational state of the device(s) controlled by it, or provide for control based on a preference of one or more people upon detecting their presence. Related methods are also described.
column15: DESMET JAMES M;;BANKS DAVID R;;REED ALEX CHRISTOPHER;;BORDERS MARCUS LANDON;;BISHOP JASON

column12: FAN WITH LEARNING MODE
column13: FAN WITH LEARNING MODE A fan, such as a ceiling fan, includes a learning mode of operation. This learning mode may permit a user to input a desired speed for the fan for a given condition, such as ambient temperature, and adjustments for other conditions would be automatically determined based on the user input. A subsequent selection of fan speed at that condition (such as, for example, for a different user) or a different condition setting would also be obtained, either during initialization or later, and then used as an updated measure of the desired fan speed for the condition. Related methods of controlling the operation of a fan are also disclosed. Figure . 13

column12: PROPERTY METADATA NAVIGATION AND ASSIGNMENT
column13: A property tree user interface permits user assignment of values to metadata properties and user navigation of data, within a system that includes a data storage subsystem in which data items are organized and queried by way of properties. The property tree includes nodes that expose properties of data items. A user may interact with the property tree in order to effect an assignement of a property, in which case the value associated with the property in the data storage subsystem is modified. User input with respect to the property tree may also be indicative of a query of data storage, in which case a browsable view of data items responsive to the query is displayed. The property tree may also display nodes that represent folders within a hierarchical file system, nodes that represent properties with inherent hierarchy, and nodes that represent user-defined hierarchical properties.

column12: Property tree for metadata navigation and assignment
column13: - 14 A computer-implemented method of user navigation of data in a computer system having a graphical user interface and a data storage subsystem in which data items are organized and queried by way of metadata properties. The method includes displaying a property tree, the property tree having a plurality of nodes exposing properties of the data items, wherein displaying the property tree includes displaying one of the plurality of nodes with an adjacent button for exposing the properties of the data items; simultaneously displaying a list view, wherein the list view is a set of the data items organized by a particular property; receiving a user input that queries the data storage subsystem with a criterion; in response to the user input, displaying in the list view the set of data items organized by the particular property meeting the criterion; receiving an indication of a selection of one or more data items of the set of data items displayed in the list view; receiving a second user input indicating one of the plurality of nodes; and applying the exposed properties associated with the indicated one of the plurality of nodes to the particular property of the selected one or more data items such the organization of the set of data items in response to the criterion is modified. column12: PROPERTY TREE FOR METADATA NAVIGATION AND ASSIGNMENT
column13: A PROPERTY TREE (203) USER INTERFACE PERMITS USER ASSIGNMENT OF VALUES TO METADATA PROPERTIES AND USER NAVIGATION OF DATA, WITHIN A SYSTEM THAT INCLUDES A DATA STORAGE SUBSYSTEM IN WHICH DATA ITEMS ARE ORGANIZED AND QUERIED BY WAY OF PROPERTIES. THE PROPERTY TREE INCLUDES NODES (209) THAT EXPOSE PROPERTIES OF DATA ITEMS (205). A USER MAY INTERACT WITH THE PROPERTY TREE (203) IN ORDER TO EFFECT AN ASSIGNMENT OF A PROPERTY, IN WHICH CASE THE VALUE ASSOCIATED WITH THE PROPERTY IN THE DATA STORAGE SUBSYSTEM IS MODIFIED. USER INPUT WITH RESPECT TO THE PROPERTY TREE MAY ALSO BE INDICATIVE OF A QUERY OF DATA STORAGE (105), IN WHICH CASE A BROWSABLE VIEW OF DATA ITEMS (201) RESPONSIVE TO THE QUERY IS DISPLAYED. column12: PROPERTY METADATA NAVIGATION AND ASSIGMENT
column13: A property tree user interface permits user assignment of values to metadata properties and user navigation of data, within a system that includes a data storage subsystem in which data items are organized and queried by way of properties. The property tree (203) includes nodes that expose properties of data items. A user may interact with the property tree in order to effect an assignment of a property, in which case the value associated with the property in the data storage subsystem is modified. User input with respect to the property tree may also be indicative of a query of data storage, in which case a browsable view (205) of data items responsive to the query is displayed. The property tree may also display nodes that represent folders within a hierarchical file system, nodes that represent properties with inherent hierarchy, and nodes that represent user-defined hierarchical properties.

column12: Property metadata navigation and assignment
column13: In a computer system having a graphical user interface and a data storage subsystem, a computer-implemented method of assigning values to properties comprises first displaying a property tree; receiving an indication of a selection of one or more data items of the set of data items residing in the data storage systems; receiving a user input indicating one of the revealed sub-nodes thereby defining a new value for the selected one or more data items; in response to the user input modifying the metadata properties of the selected one or more data items associated with the indicated one of the sub-nodes to be the new value as stored in the data storage subsystem; and second displaying the property tree including the new value is associated with the indicated one of the sub-nodes. The property tree has a plurality of property nodes that can be expanded to reveal sub-nodes. Each of the sub-nodes represents metadata properties of a set of data items. The metadata properties are of a type consistent with the expanded one of the property nodes. The set of data items are organized and queried by way of the metadata properties. In a computer system having a graphical user interface and a data storage subsystem in which data items are organized and queried by way of metadata properties a computer-implemented method of user navigation of data, comprises displaying a property tree; simultaneously displaying a list view; receiving a user input that queries the data storage subsystem with a criterion; in response to the user input displaying in the list view the set of data items organized by the particular property meeting the criteria; receiving an indication of a selection of one or more data items of the set of data items displayed in the list view; receiving a second user input indicating one of the plurality of nodes; and applying the exposed properties associated with the indicated one of the plurality of nodes to the particular property of the selected one or more data items such the organization of the set of data items in response to the criteria is modified. The property tree has a plurality of nodes exposing properties of the data items. The list view is a set of the data items organized by a particular property.
column15: MOORE JASON F;;VAN DOK CORNELIUS K;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;ANTHONY COLIN R;;BANKS RICHARD M

column12: Metadataegenskapsnavigasjon og -tilordning
column13: Et egenskapstre-brukergrensesnitt gjør det mulig for brukeren å tilordne verdier til metadata-egenskaper og brukernavigasjon i data innenfor et system som innbefatter et datalagringsundersystem der dataenheter er organisert og blir forespurt ved hjelp av egenskaper. Egenskapstreet innbefatter knutepunkter som fremviser egenskaper til dataenheter. En bruker kan samhandle med egenskapstreet for å lede til en tilordning av en egenskap, der i dette tilfellet verdien som assosieres med datalagringsundersystemet blir modifisert. Inngangsdata fra brukeren i forhold til egenskapstreet kan også indikere en forespørsel om datalagring, og dersom dette er tilfellet, blir en visning for skumlesning av dataenheter som svar på forespørselen fremvist. Egenskapstreet kan også vise knutepunkter som representerer mapper innenfor et hierarkisk filsystem, knutepunkter som representerer egenskaper med eget hierarki og knutepunkter som representerer brukerdefinerte hierarkiske egenskaper.

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM
column13: An apparatus is provided for controlling environmental conditions using a fan and a light in connection with a building having a space including a partition, such as a wall. The apparatus may include a control adapted for being mounted to the partition and for coordinating the control of the fan and the light based on a sensed condition, such as temperature or occupancy. Groups of like devices for controlling environmental conditions may be similarly controlled, such as using control. Control may also provide an indication of an operational state of the device(s) controlled by it, or provide for control based on a preference of one or more people upon detecting their presence. Related methods are also described.
column15: DESMET JAMES;;TABER CHRISTIAN;;BANKS DAVID;;HOLLAN JASON;;SMITH CAREY;;QUINN ED;;LESSER THOMAS;;SARKISIAN DYLAN;;REED ALEX;;BORDERS MARCUS;;BISHOP JASON

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM UTILIZING CIRCULATING FANS
column13: A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.
column15: DESMET JAMES;;TABER CHRISTIAN;;BANKS DAVID;;HOLLAN JASON;;SMITH CAREY;;QUINN ED;;LESSER THOMAS;;SASKISIAN DYLAN

column12: Fan with learning mode
column13: A fan, such as a ceiling fan, includes a learning mode of operation. This learning mode may permit a user to input a desired speed for the fan for a given condition, such as ambient temperature, and adjustments for other conditions would be automatically determined based on the user input. A subsequent selection of fan speed at that condition (such as, for example, for a different user) or a different condition setting would also be obtained, either during initialization or later, and then used as an updated measure of the desired fan speed for the condition. Related methods of controlling the operation of a fan are also disclosed.
column15: DESMET JAMES M;;REED ALEX;;OLESON RICHARD A;;WHITE MARSHALL;;BISHOP JASON;;LENSER RICHARD;;BANKS DAVID R

Related methods of controlling the operation of a fan are also disclosed.

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM UTILIZING CIRCULATING FANS
column13: A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.

column12: System og fremgangsmate for filtrering og organisering av elementer basert pa felles egenskaper og trekk
column13: Et system og en fremgangsmåte for å filtrere og organisere elementer fra datamaskin-lagringsenheter basert på felles egenskaper og trekk. Ifølge ett aspekt ved oppfinnelsen tilveiebringes filtre for å manipulere elementene. Filtrene er hovedsaklig verktøy for å snevre inn et sett av elementer. I én utførelsesform genereres filtrene dynamisk basert på egenskapene ved de individuelle elementene. Systemet anvender virtuelle filmapper. De virtuelle filmappene viser vanlige filer og filmapper for brukere i forskjellige fremvisninger basert på disses metadata i stedet for på oppbygningen av det underliggende filsystemet på lagringsmediet. Ifølge et annet aspekt ved oppfinnelsen tilveiebringes hurtiglenker. I én utførelsesform er hurtiglenker et sett av forhåndsdefinerte lenker (for eksempel tilveiebragt på venstre side av fremvisningen) som kan klikkes på for å generere ønskede fremvisninger av elementsettene. Ifølge et annet aspekt ved oppfinnelsen tilveiebringes biblioteker. Biblioteker består av store grupper av anvendelige typer elementer som kan assosieres med hverandre.
column15: DEVORCHIK DAVID GEORGE;;MOORE JASON F;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L;;KAASTEN SHAUN A;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR FILTERING AND ORGANIZING ITEMS BASED ON COMMON ELEMENTS
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: Systems and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;RELJA IVANOVIC;;DE VORCHIK DAVID D;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: Stack icons representing multiple objects
column13: The features described herein are directed to a method and system for use in a computing environment for representing files stored in stacks by using a stack icon. The stack icon may include multiple thumbnail images as top elements, and may use common characteristics among the files to define the appearance of the stack. The system may also use metadata or file characteristics (e.g., time of last edit, size, etc.) to identify one file for top representation in the stack icon. The system may additionally include an empty stack icon, a generic stack icon, property based icons, and custom thumbnail icons.

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM UTILIZING CIRCULATING FANS
column13: Abstract of the Disclosure A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.
column15: SARKISIAN DYLAN;;DESMET JAMES M;;TABER CHRISTIAN R;;BANKS DAVID R;;HOLLAN C JASON;;SMITH J CAREY;;QUINN ED;;LESSER THOMAS

column12: System and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column13: A system for filtering items comprises: a display; a means for providing a plurality of display objects on the display that each represent one or more items; a means for providing a filter area on the display in which a user can enter a filter term; a means for receiving a filter term entered by the user in the filter area; a means for filtering the items represented by the display objects based on the filter term and a means for modifying the display objects that are provided on the display so as to represent the items that have the metadata property that corresponds to the filter term in response to the filtering of the items. One or more of the modified display objects comprises a virtual folder. The virtual folders include numerical representations of the number of items that the virtual folders contain. The filtering of the items causes the numerical representations to be correspondingly reduced. A library is provided that includes a collection of items and a set of tools for manipulating the items of the library. The filter term is used for filtering the items of the library and the library comprises a shell browser.
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;DE VORCHIK DAVID D;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR FILTERING AND ORGANIZING ITEMS BASED ON COMMON ELEMENTS
column13: A system (600) and method for filtering (620) and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements (SB). In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters (621) are a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters (621) are dynamically generated based on the properties of separate items (651, 652, 654). The system (600) utilizes virtual folders. Virtual folders expose regular files (651, 652, 654) and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g. located on the left side of the display (600) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries (641) are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items (644) that can be associated together.

column12: System and method for displaying stack icons
column13: The present invention is directed to a method and system for use in a computing environment for representing files stored in stacks. The method includes providing a set of stack icons, each icon in the set having a stack height representing a range of stack sizes. The method additionally includes determining a stack size for a selected stack and selecting and displaying an appropriate stack icon from the set of stack icons based on the determined stack size. The selected stack may be stored within one of multiple libraries. Accordingly a distinct set of icons relevant to each library may be stored for each library. The icons may visibly convey information pertaining to the relevant library. Accordingly, the method may include representing a selected stack by determining an appropriate library and an appropriate stack height and displaying a corresponding icon. The system may additionally include an empty stack icon, a generic stack icon, property based icons, and custom thumbnail icons.
column15: BANKS RICHARD M;;CUMMINS CHARLES;;DE VORCHIK DAVID G;;GUSMORINO PAUL A;;IVANOVIC RELJA B;;LAM JENNY T;;MOORE JASON F

column12: System and Method for Filtering and Organizing Items Based on Common Elements
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements is provided. Filters can be provided for manipulating the items, which serve as tools for narrowing down a set of items. The filters can be dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system can utilize virtual folders. The virtual folders can expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. Quick links can be provided, which serve as a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. Libraries, which can provide large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together, may also be used.
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;DE VORCHIK DAVID G;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: Systems, methods, and user interfaces for storing, searching, navigating, and retrieving electronic information
column13: Computer system navigation tools provide “links” to various different files, lists, folders, and/or other storage elements and allow users to organize files, e.g., by hierarchical properties, lists, auto lists, folders, and the like. Such systems and methods allow users to assign properties to a file (optionally in a hierarchical manner), to change assigned properties, to search, view, and retrieve information based on the assigned properties, and the like.
column15: DEVORCHIK DAVID G;;WONG LYON K F;;GUSMORINO PAUL A;;CUTSINGER PAUL L;;MCKEE TIMOTHY P;;MOORE JASON;;BANKS RICHARD M

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR FILTERING AND ORGANIZING ITEMS BASED ON COMMON ELEMENTS
column13: A system (600) and method for filtering (620) and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements (SB). In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters (621) are a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters (621) are dynamically generated based on the properties of separate items (651, 652, 654). The system (600) utilizes virtual folders. Virtual folders expose regular files (651, 652, 654) and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g. located on the left side of the display (600) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries (641) are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items (644) that can be associated together.
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;DE VORCHIK DAVID D;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: Integrated thermal comfort control system utilizing circulating fans
column13: A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.
column15: SARKISIAN DYLAN;;DESMET JAMES M;;TABER CHRISTIAN R;;BANKS DAVID R;;HOLLAN C JASON;;SMITH J CAREY;;QUINN ED;;LESSER THOMAS

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR FILTERING AND ORGANIZING ITEMS BASED ON COMMON ELEMENTS
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: Systems, methods, and user interfaces for storing, searching, navigating, and retrieving electronic information
column13: Computer system navigation tools provide “links” to various different files, lists, folders, and/or other storage elements and allow users to organize files, e.g., by hierarchical properties, lists, auto lists, folders, and the like. Such systems and methods allow users to assign properties to a file (optionally in a hierarchical manner), to change assigned properties, to search, view, and retrieve information based on the assigned properties, and the like.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR FILTERING AND ORGANIZING ITEMS BASED ON COMMON ELEMENTS
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: Integrated thermal comfort control system utilizing circulating fans
column13: A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.

column12: SEARCHING, NAVIGATING, AND RETRIEVING ELECTRONIC INFORMATION
column13: Computer system navigation tools provide 'links' to various different files, lists, folders, and/or other storage elements (7C) and allow users to organize files, e.g., by hierarchical properties, lists, auto lists, folders, and the like (5). Such systems and methods allow users to assign properties to a file (optionally in a hierarchical manner) (3), to change assigned properties, to search, view, and retrieve information based on the assigned properties, and the like.

column12: System and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column13: In a computer system having a display and a memory for storing items with metadata properties, a method of filtering items comprises representing a plurality of items on the display. The individual items within the plurality of items have metadata properties and a metadata property is a category of metadata and a metadata value is the entry in a metadata property for a specific item. The method further comprises determining a common metadata property that is associated with at least two of the plurality of items; selecting a first metadata value from an item having the common metadata property as a filter term; representing the filter term on the display; receiving a user selection of the filter term; and responsive to the user selection, reducing the items that are represented on the display by representing on the display only those of the items that have the common metadata property that corresponds to the filter term.
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;DE VORCHIK DAVID D;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: Integrated thermal comfort control system utilizing circulating fans
column13: A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.

column12: Stack icons representing multiple objects
column13: The features described herein are directed to a method and system for use in a computing environment for representing files stored in stacks. The method includes providing a set of stack icons, each icon in the set having a stack height representing a range of stack sizes. The method additionally includes determining a stack size for a selected stack and selecting and displaying an appropriate stack icon from the set of stack icons based on the determined stack size. The selected stack may be stored within one of multiple libraries. Accordingly a distinct set of icons relevant to each library may be stored for each library. The icons may visibly convey information pertaining to the relevant library. Accordingly, the method may include representing a selected stack by determining an appropriate library and an appropriate stack height and displaying a corresponding icon. The stack icon may include multiple thumbnail images as top elements, and may use common characteristics among the files to define the appearance of the stack. The system may also use metadata or file characteristics (e.g., time of last edit, size, etc.) to identify one file for top representation in the stack icon. The system may additionally include an empty stack icon, a generic stack icon, property based icons, and custom thumbnail icons.

column12: System and Method for Filtering and Organizing Items Based on Common Elements
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements is provided. Filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. The filters can be dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk.
column15: KAASTEN SHAUN A;;MOORE JASON F;;TUBBS KENNETH M;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;DE VORCHIK DAVID G;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L

column12: System and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements is provided. Filters can be provided for manipulating the items, which serve as tools for narrowing down a set of items. The filters can be dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system can utilize virtual folders. The virtual folders can expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. Quick links can be provided, which serve as a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. Libraries, which can provide large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together, may also be used.

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM UTILIZING CIRCULATING FANS
column13: Abstract of the Disclosure A system for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.

column12: SEARCHING, NAVIGATING, AND RETRIEVING ELECTRONIC INFORMATION
column13: Computer system navigation tools provide "links" to various different files, lists, folders, and/or other storage elements (7C) and allow users to organize files, e.g., by hierarchical properties, lists, auto lists, folders, and the like (5). column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: System and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: INTEGRATED THERMAL COMFORT CONTROL SYSTEM UTILIZING CIRCULATING FANS
column13: A system (100) for providing thermal comfort for a person within a space comprising a plurality of interconnected zones, such as a single room in a residence, commercial establishment, or industrial location. At least one fan (110) is positioned in each zone, which may be an overhead fan mounted to a ceiling common to two or more of the zones, and a sensor (130, 140, 150, 180) is provided for sensing a condition in at least one of the zones. A controller (160) is adapted for controlling the fan in the at least one zone independent of another fan based on the sensed condition in the at least one zone including the controlled fan. Related aspects of a thermal comfort control system and methods are also disclosed.
column15: DESMET JAMES M;;TABER CHRISTIAN R;;BANKS DAVID R;;HOLLAN C JASON;;SMITH J CAREY;;QUINN ED;;LESSER THOMAS;;DYLAN SARKISIAN

column12: Sistema e método para filtrar e organizar itens baseado em elementos comuns
column13: "SISTEMA E MéTODO PARA FILTRAR E ORGANIZAR ITENS BASEADO EM ELEMENTOS COMUNS". Trata-se de um sistema e um método para filtrar e organizar itens a partir de memórias do computador baseado em elementos comuns. De acordo com um aspecto da invenção, são proporcionados filtros para manipular os itens. Os filtros são essencialmente ferramentas para reduzir um conjunto de itens. Em uma modalidade, os filtros são dinamicamente gerados baseado nas propriedades dos itens separados. O sistema utiliza pastas virtuais. As pastas virtuais expõem arquivos normais e pastas para usuários em vistas diferentes baseado em seus metadados ao invés de na estrutura física real do sistema de arquivos subjacente no disco. De acordo com outro aspecto da invenção, são proporcionadas ligações rápidas. Em uma modalidade, as ligações rápidas são um conjunto de ligações predefinidas (por exemplo, localizadas no lado esquerdo da exibição) que podem ser clicadas para gerar vistas úteis dos conjuntos de itens. De acordo com outro aspecto da invenção, são proporcionadas bibliotecas. As bibliotecas consistem de grandes grupos de tipos de itens utilizáveis que podem ser associados.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR RESOURCE ALLOCATION OPTIMIZATION FOR TASK EXECUTION
column13: A system configured to optimize resource allocation efficiency obtains a task. The system identifies a set of task features associated with the task, where the task features include a description, requirements, time criticality level, resource needs with respect to the task. The system identifies one or more entities impacted by the task. The system notifies the one or more entities to update the task features. The system receives the updated task features. The system determines a performance level associated with the task based on the updated task features. The system determines a priority level for performing the task based on the performance level and the updated task features such that a predefined rule is met. The predefined rule is defined to optimize at least one of task completion time, task result quality, and resource allocation efficiency.

column12: System og fremgangsmate for utnyttelse av virtuelle mapper
column13: Det er beskrevet et system og en fremgangsmåte for anvendelse av virtuelle mapper (fig.3). De virtuelle mappene viser vanhge filer og mapper til brukere i forskjellige brukerutsnitt basert på deres metadata istedenfor den aktuelle, fysisk underhggende filsys- temstrukturen på platen (fig.3). De virtuelle mappene (308) inneholder samlinger av elementer. Systemet innbefatter en mappeprosessor som fremskaffer søk fra en bruker (302) og en relasjonsdatabase (304) for lagring av informasjon om elementene. Mappepro- sessoren fremskaffer først et søk fra en bruker (302) og videresender søket til relasjonsdatabasen (304). Relasjonsdatabasen leverer resultater tilbake til mappeprosessoren (306), og basert på resultatene fra relasjonsdatabasen leverer mappeprosessoren resul- tatene til brukeren som virtuelle mapper (308). Bruk- ere er i stand til å arbeide med de virtuelle mappene ved direkte manipulering (feks. klikking på og frekk- ing, kopiering, innliming, osv.)

column12: System og fremgangsmate til forvaltning av data ved hjelp av statiske lister
column13: Det er tilveiebrakt en fremgangsmåte og et system hvor statiske lister letter vilkårlig gruppering av dataelementer uavhengig av deres posisjoner og på måter som er av betydning for brukeren. En stat isk liste er et sett med dataelementer definert av et rotelement, en retning og inngangsrelasjonene med rotelementet i vedkommende retning. Den statiske listen definerer også de egenskapene som hver inngangsrelasjon i listen må ha. Verb er tilveiebrakt for å ordne en statisk liste. Et verb er en handling som kan utføres på dataelementene i den statiske listen, og innbefatter blant annet å flytte, å kopiere, å tilføye, å fjerne og slette. En oversikt blir tilveiebrakt for å spesifisere karakteristikker for visning av data fra en statisk liste, innbefattende synlighet, rekkefølge og formatering blant andre karakteristikker.

column12: sistema e método utilizando pastas virtuais
column13: "SISTEMA E MéTODO UTILIZANDO PASTAS VIRTUAIS". Um sistema e método utilizando pastas virtuais (FIG. 3). As pastas virtuais expõem arquivos e pastas regulares a usuários em diferentes visualizações baseadas em seus metadados ao invés da estrutura de sistema de arquivos de base física real no disco (FIG. 3). As pastas virtuais (308) contêm coleções de itens. O sistema inclui um processador de pasta que obtém solicitações a partir de um usuário (302) e uma base de dados relacional (304) para armazenar informação sobre os itens. O processador de pasta primeiro obtém uma solicitação de um usuário (302) e passa a solicitação à base de dados relacional (304). A base de dados relacional fornece resultados de volta ao processador de pasta (306), e baseado nos resultados da base de dados relacional, o processador de pasta fornece os resultados ao usuário como pastas virtuais (308). Usuários são capazes de trabalhar com pastas virtuais através de manipulação direta (por exemplo, clicando e arrastando, copiando, colando, etc.).

column12: File system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations
column13: A file system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, a wide scope of items may be available. In other words, the system is able to represent items from multiple physical locations (e.g., different hard drives, different computers, different network locations, etc.) so that to a user all the items appear to be from one location. The file system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, non-file items may be represented in the virtual folders. In other words, files that are stored in memory are located in a physical store. The virtual folders can be made to include items that are not currently represented in the physical store. Examples of non-file items are e-mails and contacts.

column12: Surgical instruments and end effectors therefor
column13: An end effector for use with a surgical instrument is disclosed. The end effector comprises a first jaw, a second jaw, wherein the first jaw is movable relative to the second jaw to transition the end effector between an open configuration and an approximated configuration to clamp tissue between the first jaw and the second jaw, and a camming assembly. The camming assembly comprises a first camming member comprising a first distal camming portion, a first proximal camming portion, and a first flexible portion extending between the first distal camming portion and the first proximal camming portion. The camming assembly further comprises a second camming member and a connector at least partially disposed between the first camming member and the second camming member, wherein the camming assembly is movable relative to the end effector to transition the end effector to the approximated configuration.

column12: System and method utilizing virtual folders
column13: A system and method utilizing virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. The virtual folders contain collections of items. The system includes a folder processor that obtains queries from a user and a relational database for storing information about the items. The folder processor first obtains a query from a user and passes the query to the relational database. The relational database provides results back to the folder processor, and based on the results from the relational database, the folder processor provides the results to the user as virtual folders. Users are able to work with the virtual folders through direct manipulation (e.g., clicking and dragging, copying, pasting, etc.).

column12: SURGICAL INSTRUMENTS AND END EFFECTORS THEREFOR
column13: An end effector includes a first jaw and a second jaw, the first jaw movable relative to the second jaw to transition the end effector between an open configuration and an approximated configuration to clamp tissue therebetween. The end effector may also include a camming assembly movable along a curved path. The camming assembly includes a first camming member which includes a first distal camming portion, a first proximal camming portion, and a first flexible portion extending between the first distal camming portion and the first proximal camming portion. The camming assembly includes a second camming member and a connector at least partially disposed between the first camming member and the second camming member, wherein the camming assembly is movable relative to the end effector to exert a camming force against the first jaw and the second jaw to transition the end effector to the approximated configuration.
column15: WITT DAVID A;;HUANG ZHIFAN F;;DIETZ TIMOTHY G;;BANKS RAYMOND M;;ALDRIDGE JEFFREY L;;BERNATH STEVE G;;NORVELL DAVID K;;WEIZMAN PATRICK A;;HARRIS JASON L

column12: System and method for filtering and organizing items based on common elements
column13: A system and method for filtering and organizing items from computer memories based on common elements. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, filters are provided for manipulating the items. The filters are essentially tools for narrowing down a set of items. In one embodiment, the filters are dynamically generated based on the properties of the separate items. The system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, quick links are provided. In one embodiment, quick links are a set of predefined links (e.g., located on the left side of the display) that can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, libraries are provided. Libraries consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together.

column12: SYSTEM AMD METHOD UTILIZING VIRTUAL FOLDERS
column13: A system and method utilizing virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. The virtual folders (308) contain collections of items. The system includes a folder processor that obtains queries from a user (302) and a relational database (304) for storing information about the items. The folder processor first obtains a query from a user (302) and passes the query to the relational database (304). The relational database provides results back to the folder processor (306), and based on the results from the relational database, the folder processor provides the results to the user as virtual folders (308). Users are able to work with the virtual folders through direct manipulation (e.g., clicking and dragging, copying, pasting, etc.).

column12: FILE SYSTEM FOR DISPLAYING ITEMS OF DIFFERENT TYPES AND FROM DIFFERENT PHYSICAL LOCATIONS
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To make a storage location of an original retrieval result be known when retrieval results of various items are stored in a virtual folder.

SOLUTION: A property of metadata regarding a virtual folder and a physical location of a storage source are stored in a virtual folder description database, and item display in the virtual folder is switched to display indicating the storage source on the basis of the stored data. File items and non-file items like e-mail are included in items for retrieval.

column12: Surgical instruments and end effectors therefor
column13: Various forms of surgical instruments are disclosed. In various embodiments, an end effector having operable and closable jaws is attached to a distal end of an elongate shaft such that portions of the jaws are axially offset from the elongate shaft. Other jaw embodiments are coupled to an actuation arrangement that permits portions of the jaws to be moved out of axial alignment with the elongate shaft. Other jaw embodiments are configured to facilitate tissue dissection. Electrosurgical instruments are also disclosed. One embodiment employs a flexible electrode that is conformable to tissue.

column12: SURGICAL INSTRUMENTS AND END EFFECTORS THEREFOR
column13: An end effector includes a first jaw and a second jaw, the first jaw movable relative to the second jaw to transition the end effector between an open configuration and an approximated configuration to clamp tissue therebetween. The end effector may also include a camming assembly movable along a curved path. The camming assembly includes a first camming member which includes a first distal camming portion, a first proximal camming portion, and a first flexible portion extending between the first distal camming portion and the first proximal camming portion. The camming assembly includes a second camming member and a connector at least partially disposed between the first camming member and the second camming member, wherein the camming assembly is movable relative to the end effector to exert a camming force against the first jaw and the second jaw to transition the end effector to the approximated configuration.

column12: System and method utilizing metadata to provide virtual folders of related objects which are really in different physical locations
column13: A system and method for utilizing virtual folders are disclosed. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. The system includes a folder processor that obtains queries from a user (302) and a relational database (304) for storing information about the items. The folder processor first obtains a query from a user (302) and passes the query to the relational database (304). The relational database provides results back to the folder processor (306), and based on the results from the relational database, the folder processor provides the results to the user as virtual folders (308). A system and method for manipulating virtual folders are also disclosed where direct manipulation actions of the virtual folders are provided. The direct manipulation can include clicking and dragging of a virtual folder. The clicking and dragging a virtual folder to another virtual folder performs the function of copying the items of the first virtual folder to the second virtual folder. The virtual folders (308) contain collections of items and items are contained within a virtual folder on the basis of having a selected metadata property that is the basis for the virtual folder, and the action of copying the items from a first virtual folder to a second virtual folder is implemented at least in part by adding the metadata property of the second virtual folder to each of the items from the first virtual folder.

column12: File system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations
column13: A file system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, a wide scope of items may be available. In other words, the system is able to represent items from multiple physical locations (e.g., different hard drives, different computers, different network locations, etc.) so that to a user all the items appear to be from one location. The file system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, non-file items may be represented in the virtual folders. In other words, files that are stored in memory are located in a physical store. The virtual folders can be made to include items that are not currently represented in the physical store. Examples of non-file items are e-mails and contacts.

column12: File system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations
column13: A system for displaying items comprises a means for defining a scope of physical memory locations from which items are to be drawn. The scope comprises the present computer memory and at least one other physical location. The system also comprises a means for drawing items from the physical locations as defined in the scope in response to a query. The items include both file and non file items. The system also comprises a means for presenting the items drawn from the query in a view on a display and a means for providing virtual folders that represent a plurality of items in the view of the display.

column15: SHELDON DAVID JOEL;;DEVORCHIK DAVID GEORGE;;GUZAK CHRIS J;;MOORE JASON F;;BANKS RICHARD M;;MINER PATRICE L;;KAASTEN SHAUN A;;BALLOU NATHANIEL H;;CHALIVENDRA SASANKA C

column12: Filsystem for fremvisning av elementer av forskjellige typer og fra forskjellige fysiske steder
column13: Et filsystem for å vise elementer av forskjellige typer og fra forskjellige fysiske lagringssteder. Ifølge ett aspekt ved oppfinnelsen kan et bredt kildeområde for filer være tilgjengelig. Med andre ord er systemet i stand til årepresentere elementer fra flere fysiske lagringssteder (for eksempel forskjellige harddisker, forskjellige datamaskiner, forskjellige nettverkssteder, etc.) på en slik måte at det for en bruker ser ut som om alle elementene befinner seg på samme sted. Filsystemet anvender virtuelle filmapper. De virtuelle filmappene i viser vanlige filer og filmapper for brukere i forskjellige fremvisninger basert på disses metadata i stedet for på oppbygningen av det underliggende filsystemet på lagringsmediet. Ifølge et annet aspekt ved oppfinnelsen kan elementer som ikke er filer representeres i de virtuelle filmappene. Med andre ord befinner lagrede filer seg i et fysisk lager, mens de virtuelle filmappene vil kunne inneholde elementer som når de vises ikke er representert i det fysiske lageret. Eksempler på elementer som ikke er filer er e-poster og kontakter.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR MANAGING DATA USING STATIC LISTS
column13: A method and system are provided in which staticlists (310) is a type of static set. The static list (310) comprises a list item (320) comprises a list item (320) and a list entry relationship type (330). The list item (320) is root Item and the list entry relationship type (330) defines the set of properties and direction that each relationship in the list must have in an entry template (340) that specifies property names (350) for each properties. A view is provided to specify characteristics for displaying data from a static list, including visibility, order and formatting, among other characteristics.
column15: MOORE JASON F;;BANKS RICHARD M;;VAN DOK CORNELIS K;;DE VORCHIK DAVID G;;MCKEE TIMOTHY P;;SMITH WALTER R;;GUZAK CHRIS J;;IVANOVIC RELJA;;BELT JEFFREY C

column12: System and method for managing data using static lists
column13: A method and system are provided in which static lists facilitate arbitrary grouping of items of data independent of their locations and in ways that are meaningful to the user. A static list is a set of items defined by a root item, a direction, and the entry relationships with that root item in that direction. The static list also defines the properties that each entry relationship in the list is required to have. Verbs are provided to manage a static list. A verb is an action that may be performed on the items in the static list, and includes, among others, move, copy, add, remove, and delete. A view is provided to specify characteristics for displaying data from a static list, including visibility, order, and formatting, among other characteristics.

column12: METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR BYPASSING ARTERIAL OBSTRUCTIONS AND/OR PERFORMING OTHER TRANSVASCULAR PROCEDURES
column13: This invention concerns methods, devices, and systems for re-vascularization, and/or performing other medical procedures at vascular or non-vascular intra-corporeal locations within a mammalian body. The methods generally comprise the formation of at least one extravascular passageway (10a) from a blood vessel to a vascular or non-vascular target location. In the re-vascularization methods the extravascular passageway is utilized for blood flow. In the medical procedure methods the extravascular passageway (10a) is utilized as a conduit for accessing or performing procedures at the vascular or non-vascular target location. Also disclosed are catheter devices and systems which are useable to form the extravascular passageways (10a, 10b) of the invention, as well as apparatus for modifying, maintaining and/or closing such extravascular passageways.

column12: FILE SYSTEM FOR DISPLAYING ITEMS OF DIFFERENT TYPES AND FROMDIFFERENT PHYSICAL LOCATIONS
column13: A file system for displaying items of different types and from different physical locations. In accordance with one aspect of the invention, a wide scope of items may be available. In other words, the system is able to represent items from multiple physical locations (e.g., different hard drives, different computers, different network locations, etc.) so that to a user all the items appear to be from one location. The file system utilizes virtual folders. The virtual folders expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. In accordance with another aspect of the invention, non- file items may be represented in the virtual folders. In other words, files that are stored in memory are located in a physical store. The virtual folders can be made to include items that are not currently represented in the physical store. Examples of non-file items are e-mails and contacts.

column12: Sistema e método para gerenciar dados com utilização de listas estáticas
column13: "SISTEMA E MéTODO PARA GERENCIAR DADOS COM UTILIZAçãO DE LISTAS ESTáTICAS". São providos um método e sistema nos quais listas estáticas facilitam agrupamentos arbitrários de itens de dados independente de suas localizações e de maneiras que são significativas ao usuário. Uma lista estática é um conjunto de itens definido por um item raiz, uma direção e relacionamentos de entrada com esse item raiz nessa direção. A lista estática também define as propriedades que cada relacionamento de entrada na lista precisa ter. São providos verbos para gerenciar uma lista estática. Um verbo é uma ação que pode ser executada nos itens na lista estática, e inclui entre outros, mover, copiar, adicionar, remover e deletar. Uma vista é provida para especificar características para exibir dados a partir de uma lista estática, incluindo visibilidade, ordem e formatação, entre outras características.

column12: System and Method for Managing Data Using Static Lists
column13: A method and system are provided in which static lists facilitate arbitrary grouping of items of data independent of their locations and in ways that are meaningful to the user. A static list is a set of items defined by a root item, a direction, and the entry relationships with that root item in that direction. The static list also defines the properties that each entry relationship in the list is required to have. Verbs are provided to manage a static list. A verb is an action that may be performed on the items in the static list, and includes, among others, move, copy, add, remove, and delete. A view is provided to specify characteristics for displaying data from a static list, including visibility, order, and formatting, among other characteristics.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR MANAGING DATA USING STATIC LISTS
column13: A method and system are provided in which static lists facilitate arbitrary grouping of items of data independent of their locations and in ways that are meaningful to the user. A static list is a set of items defined by a root item, a direction, and the entry relationships with that root item in that direction. The static list also defines the properties that each entry relationship in the list is required to have. Verbs are provided to manage a static list. A verb is an action that may be performed on the items in the static list, and includes, among others, move, copy, add, remove, and delete. A view is provided to specify characteristics for displaying data from a static list, including visibility, order, and formatting, among other characteristics.

column12: Cápsula de sistema de arquivos
column13: "CáPSULA DE SISTEMA DE ARQUIVOS". é provida uma cápsula de sistema de arquivos. Um aspecto da cápsula fornece pastas virtuais que expõem arquivos e pastas regulares aos usuários em diferentes vistas com base em seus metadados, e não na estrutura física real do sistema de arquivos subjacente no disco. Usuários podem trabalhar com as pastas virtuais através de manipulação direta (por exemplo, clicando e arrastando, copiando, colando, etc.). Filtros são providos para estreitar conjuntos de itens. São providos atalhos rápidos que podem ser clicados para gerar vistas úteis dos conjuntos de itens. São providas bibliotecas que consistem de grandes grupos de tipos de itens utilizáveis que podem ser associados uns com os outros, juntamente com funções e ferramentas relacionadas aos itens. é provida uma barra de endereços virtuais que compreende uma pluralidade de segmentos, cada segmento correspondendo a um filtro para selecionar conteúdo. é provido um paginador de cápsula com o qual usuários podem identificar facilmente um item com base nos metadados associados com esse item. é provido um pré-visualizador de objetos em um paginador de cápsula que é configurado para exibir uma pluralidade de itens que representam múltiplos tipos de itens.

column12: System and method for managing data using static lists
column13: A method and system are provided in which static lists facilitate arbitrary grouping of items of data independent of their locations and in ways that are meaningful to the user. A static list is a set of items defined by a root item, a direction, and the entry relationships with that root item in that direction. The static list also defines the properties that each entry relationships in the list is required to have. Verbs are provided to manage a static list, and includes, among others, move, copy, add, remove, and delete. A view is provided to specify characteristics for displaying data from a static list, including visibility, order, and formatting, among other characteristics.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR BYPASSING ARTERIAL OBSTRUCTIONS AND/OR PERFORMING OTHER TRANSVASCULAR PROCEDURES
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide new method and device for accessing tumor, organs and tissues in order to implement surgical or intervention method without surgical incision in the body.

SOLUTION: This method generally includes formation of at least one extravascular path from a blood vessel or to a vascular or non-vascular target position. In the revascularization methods, the extravascular path is used as a conduit for accessing or implementing the method in the vascular or non-vascular target position. Further, in order to form the extravascular path, catheter instruments 100, 103, a system 138 and a device for deforming, holding and/or closing the extravascular path are used in combination.

column12: System and method for managing data using static lists
column13: A computer-implemented method for managing data in a list comprises creating a list having an item type and a relationship type; adding an item to the list by generating a list entry representing an association between an item and the item type and storing the list in a memory of a data processing device. The list entry comprises one or more item properties specified by the relationship type. A system for managing data, the system comprises a storage medium for storing items of data and a list entry template; a processing unit for operating a process to generate a list of selected items in response to a user input and a display unit for displaying a view of the items in the list, the view including a display of the property values of the entry in accordance with a display characteristic. Each entry of the list represents a reference to the item independent of the item's location in the storage medium, and each entry includes a property value generated in accordance with the list entry template.

column12: Sistema de arquivos para exibir itens de tipos diferentes e de diferentes localizações fìsicas
column13: "SISTEMA DE ARQUIVOS PARA EXIBIR ITENS DE TIPOS DIFERENTES E DE DIFERENTES LOCALIZAçõES FìSICAS". Trata-se de um sistema de arquivos para exibir itens de diferentes tipos e de diferentes localizações fisicas. De acordo com um aspecto da invenção, um amplo escopo de itens pode ser disponível. Em outras palavras, o sistema está apto a representar itens a partir de várias localizações físicas (por exemplo, diferentes controladores de disco rígido, diferentes computadores, diferentes localizações de rede, etc.) de modo que para um usuário todos os itens parecem como sendo de uma localização. o sistema de arquivos utiliza pastas virtuais. As pastas virtuais expõem arquivos normais e pastas para usuários em vistas diferentes baseado em seus metadados ao invés de na estrutura fisica real do sistema de arquivos subjacente. De acordo com outro aspecto da invenção, itens que não são arquivo podem ser representados nas pastas virtuais. Em outras palavras, arquivos que estão armazenados na memória estão localizados em um depósito físico. As pastas virtuais podem ser feitas para incluir itens que não são atualmente representados no depósito físico. Exemplos de itens que nao são arquivo são correios eletrónicos e contatos.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR CONTROLLING USER INTERFACE OF VIRTUAL ADDRESS BAR INCLUDING MULTIPLE INTERACTIVE SEGMENTS
column13: PURPOSE: A system and a method for controlling a user interface of a virtual address bar including multiple interactive segments are provided to enable a user to prescribe an address indicating a stored file from multiple file system locations and easily modify the address of the address bar, and suggest alternative selection for navigating file selection to the user. CONSTITUTION: A computing device is equipped with a processor and a memory. A storage device stores contents by connecting to the computing device. A display device displays the virtual address bar(402) by connecting to the computing device. The virtual address bar includes address segments(502-508). Each address segment is matched with a filter for selecting the contents from the contents stored in the storage device. The filter includes a virtual address for selecting the contents to be displayed to the display device.

column12: File system shell
column13: A file system shell provides virtual folders (651-655) which expose regular files and folders to users in different views, based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure. Users are able to work with the virtual folders (651-655) through direct manipulation. Filters (620-626) are provided for narrowing down sets of items. Quick links (610-613) generate useful views of the sets of items. Libraries (600) consist of large groups of usable types of items that can be associated together, along with functions and tools related to the items. A virtual address bar comprises a plurality of segments, where each segment corresponds to a filter for selecting content. A shell browser is provided with which users can readily identify an item based on the metadata associated with that item. An object previewer in a shell browser displays a plurality of items representing multiple item types.

column12: Virtual address bar user interface control
column13: A virtual address bar user interface control is presented. The virtual address bar includes a plurality of interactive segments, each segment corresponding to a predetermined filter for selecting content in a computer file system. Collectively, the interactive segments represent a virtual address for selecting content. Selecting an interactive segment in the virtual address bar causes those segments subsequent to the selected segment to be removed from the virtual address bar. A user may select a peer filter for a segment to replace that segment's current filter and removes those segments subsequent to the updated segment. The virtual address bar can be selectively configured to operate as a conventional address bar, and reconfigured to operate as a virtual address bar. Additional filter segments are added to the end of the existing filter segments. Those existing filter segments that conflict with the added segment are removed from the virtual address bar.

column12: FILE SYSTEM SHELL
column13: R file system shell is provided one aspect of the shell provides virtual folders which expose regular files and folders to users in different views based on their metadata instead of the actual physical underlying file system structure on the disk. Users are able to work with the virtual folders through direct manipulation (e.g., clicking and dragging, copying pasting, etc.). Filters are provided for narrowing down sets of item s. Quick links are provided which can be clicked on to generate useful views of the sets of items. Libraries are provided which consist of large groups of usable types of item s that can be associated together, along with functions and tools related to the items. A virtual address bar is provided which comprises a plurality of segments, each segment corresponding to a filter for selecting content. A shell browser is provided with which users c an readily identify an item based on the metadata associated with that item. An object previewer in shell browser is provided which is configured to display a plurality of item s representing multiple item types.

column12: Controle de interface de usuário de barra de endereço virtual
column13: "CONTROLE DE INTERFACE DE USUáRIO DE BARRA DE ENDEREçO VIRTUAL". é apresentado um controle de interface de usuário de barra de endereço virtual. A barra de endereço virtual inclui uma pluralidade de segmentos interativos, cada segmento correspondendo a um filtro predeterminado para selecionar conteúdo em um sistema de arquivos de computador. Coletivamente, os segmentos interativos representam um endereço virtual para selecionar conteúdo. A seleção de um segmento interativo na barra de endereço virtual faz com que os elementos subseq³entes ao segmento selecionado sejam removidos da barra de endereço virtual. Um usuário pode selecionar um filtro entre pares para um segmento substituir o filtro atual do segmento e remover os segmentos subseq³entes ao segmento atualizado. A barra de endereço virtual pode ser seletivamente configurada para operar como uma barra de endereço convencional, e reconfigurada para operar como uma barra de endereço virtual. Segmentos de filtro extras são adicionados ao final dos segmentos de filtro existentes. Os segmentos de filtro existentes que entram em conflito com o segmento adicionado são removidos da barra de endereço virtual.
